some links to sites that helped me with this project:

how to clear the screen in C++:
http://mathbits.com/MathBits/CompSci/Screen/clear.htm
http://stackoverflow.com/questions/18326415/clearing-the-screen-in-c-using-other-compilers

looked into getting a stats package to generate claims (and other features I'd like randomized):
http://www.boost.org/doc/libs/1_38_0/libs/math/doc/sf_and_dist/html/index.html
http://www.boost.org/doc/libs/master/libs/math/doc/html/dist.html
http://stackoverflow.com/questions/746364/best-library-for-statistics-in-c

installing boost:
boost libraries need to be installed:
http://stackoverflow.com/questions/22470265/how-to-install-boost-on-gnu-linux

properly renaming a directory in a git repository:
http://stackoverflow.com/questions/11183788/in-a-git-repository-how-to-properly-rename-a-directory

installing sqlite3
we'll need the development headers which can be installed using the line:
$sudo apt-get install libsqlite3-dev
http://www.databasically.com/2010/03/05/installing-sqlite-headers-on-ubuntu-sqlite3-h-not-found/

linking to sqlie3
found out I had to link to the sqlite3 library to compile programs that use the sqlite API:
http://stackoverflow.com/questions/9389344/error-undefined-reference-to-sqlite3-open

program tree:
a note on organizing a git repository
http://programmers.stackexchange.com/questions/81899/how-should-i-organize-my-source-tree
